						Mnemosyna Planetarum.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>The remembrances of planets.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="EN">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						The brauist brauerie of this World.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Superborum domitor elegans.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>The elegant conqueror of the arrogant.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="IT">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						destramente.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Dexterously.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Curanda Sola, qua[e] faciunt homines hominibus
						pra[e]stantiores; et uiros uiris digniores.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>The only things one must care for, are those which make men more outstanding than men; and men more worthy than men.</translation> <!--JG: Should I translate homines and viros differently?-->
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Quorsum doctrina, qua[e] non facit peritiorem, et efficaciorem; id est, prudentiorem,
						et fortiorem? ideoq[ue] etiam priuatim fortunatiorem; public&egrave; honoratiorem.
						Sola curanda, qua[e] parant bonum; id est, vtile, honorificum, iucundum.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Qua[e] conducunt animo, corpori, statui.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Whither a doctrine, which does not make more skilled and effective, that is, more prudent and strong? Therefore also more fortune in private and more honorable in public.
				The only things one must care for, are those which produce good things, that is, useful, honorable, and pleasant. The things which are of advantage for mind, body, and standing.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						Statim ea compinge, vnd&egrave; alios antecellas. Nec plurima Sunt: nec difficillima:
						hoc est, esse virum, vel agere, vel saltem scire, ea, quibus viri possunt viris
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						pra[e]stare.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Immediatly join those things, from which you surpass others. Neither there are very many, nor are they most difficult: this est, in order to be a man, either to do or at least to learn
			those things by which men can excell over men.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
